WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Our first talk is on RMarkdown Driven Development. Please join me in welcoming Emily Riederer.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:23.120
All right. Hi, everyone. Thank you so much for coming. My name is Emily Riederer and

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:28.360
I'm here today to talk about RMarkdown Driven Development. I assume many of us in this room

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:33.160
are already familiar with RMarkdown and what an amazing tool it is for literate programming

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:38.680
and combining both code and narrative in plain text to create an amazing variety of different

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:44.799
types of outputs. But something I'm particularly fascinated by is how RMarkdown can also be

00:00:44.799 --> 00:00:53.200
used as a prototyping tool for more advanced analytical tools. I contend that any analysis

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:59.840
that you've created in an RMarkdown document actually contains a latent underlying implicit

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:07.680
package or analytical tool that is custom tuned to solve your domain specific workflow

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:12.639
from everything from dealing with custom nuances in your data to making the specific types

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:18.839
of deliverables that the customers of your analysis need. And the goal of RMarkdown Driven

00:01:18.839 --> 00:01:24.400
Development is to take this implicit tool and make it an explicit one. We'll do this

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:30.000
by harvesting all of the assets that you've already created in that implicit tool. For

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.080
example, from the development side, you've already probably had to go through and curate

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:41.720
a wide set of packages that relate to your problem and play nicely together. And you

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:48.320
hopefully have developed in your one-off analysis a consistent set of code that works to solve

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:56.760
your problem and ideally is at least somewhat well tested and well styled. But beyond pure

00:01:56.760 --> 00:02:01.519
code development that we have to work with, we also have a lot of great design elements

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:07.599
already in place. One of the hardest parts generally of creating a software product is

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:12.279
understanding user requirements and getting deep empathy for user needs. But as the person

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:17.080
that did the original RMarkdown analysis, you get all of that for free. You understand

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:22.360
how all of the pieces of analysis need to come together, a sane workflow for doing the

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:27.520
work and processing your data, and again, answering those questions that are important

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.639
to the people that you want to share your analysis with. And finally, you have already

00:02:31.639 --> 00:02:36.720
a complete and compelling marketing example of how your latent tool goes into use and

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:42.839
can solve real-world problems in the wild. So there are five main steps to our RMarkdown

00:02:42.839 --> 00:02:48.559
driven development that I want to talk about today. And along the way, we'll talk about

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:52.960
how these steps can result in many different types of outputs and many different types

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:58.679
of analytical products. You can think about producing well-engineered single files, projects,

00:02:58.679 --> 00:03:03.119
or packages. And while I depict this as a spectrum, I think it's important to call out

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:08.080
at the beginning, there's not necessarily a clear value judgment in here. There's no

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:13.880
better or worse in terms of quality, user experience, or your talent as a coder, depending

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:19.399
on what part of the spectrum you stop at. Really, all it is, and we'll see as we go

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:25.759
through this, is whether you want to tune your final analysis tool more to solving another

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:31.279
instance of your very specific problem or a tool that solves more of a generic class

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:36.479
of problems. So now we'll go through the steps of our RMarkdown driven development one at

00:03:36.479 --> 00:03:41.160
a time. The first step's pretty easy because we don't actually have to generate anything

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:45.919
new. We just simply have to delete a lot of things that shouldn't be in our RMarkdown

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:52.360
to begin with. So for example, some of these things might include hard-coded variables,

00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:57.199
which are common when we're doing a one-off analysis. But thinking about ourselves or

00:03:57.199 --> 00:04:01.800
a future user that might want to update this analysis later on, it can be really detrimental

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:07.240
to have hard-coded variables late in our analysis that users may not realize when

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:13.000
or where they have to change. Or even worse, they might change them inconsistently some

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.320
places and not the others and introduce inconsistencies in their analysis. Instead, RMarkdown parameters

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:26.359
let us front load all of this in the YAML header of your RMarkdown document, which means

00:04:26.359 --> 00:04:30.959
that it's very easy for a future user to see exactly in front of them what changes they

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.119
need to make and have everything flow on through your analysis. Effectively then, your entire

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:42.559
RMarkdown is acting kind of like one mega function through which everything can flow.

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:47.079
This is also an effective strategy for dealing with credentials that you might not want in

00:04:47.079 --> 00:04:51.559
your final output in case you end up sharing your code with a colleague and even just for

00:04:51.559 --> 00:04:57.399
good data security practices. There's really great synergy here with the RStudio IDE because

00:04:57.399 --> 00:05:01.760
if you click knit with parameters, you can get a nice little pop-up box and replace dummy

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:06.239
credentials in your header with your actual credentials, so you've never hard-coded them

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:12.040
anywhere. Next up, I think we already learned from Jenny a little bit this morning about

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:17.679
file paths, and we know that we don't want to include global file paths in our RMarkdown

00:05:17.679 --> 00:05:23.440
because it makes it very unresilient to working in the future. Local file paths are a slight

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:28.839
improvement over these, but can still break as we change across operating systems or later

00:05:28.839 --> 00:05:33.920
on as we move our files around inside of our working directory. So best of all, we can

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:40.320
use the here package to create very resilient file paths to make sure our analysis always

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:46.279
works as planned. And finally, and this step is by far the hardest for me, sometimes we

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:51.079
have to kill our darlings. You can't let your RMarkdown be a junk drawer for code that you

00:05:51.079 --> 00:05:55.320
wrote, rabbit holes you went down, that you really, really thought would work, but then

00:05:55.320 --> 00:06:00.880
didn't end up being the direction your analysis went in. Take this time to remove package

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:05.040
loads that you didn't need and delete code experiments that you maybe have commented

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:11.279
out in your code just to create a very clean code script with a lot of hygiene on which

00:06:11.279 --> 00:06:17.880
to proceed with your refactoring. The next step in RMarkdown-driven development is simply

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:23.359
rearranging your code chunks. RMarkdown is great because it allows us to capture our

00:06:23.359 --> 00:06:27.839
thought process as we go through our analysis, but the one downside of this is our thought

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:34.040
processes are rarely linear and as a result, often neither are the resulting markdowns.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:39.200
The strategy here is to move to the top a lot of the heavy-duty infrastructure and computing

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:44.640
chunks. These can be things that set up our environment, such as library loads, data loads,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.399
and a lot of our heavy-duty computation with data wrangling, data cleaning, model fitting,

00:06:49.399 --> 00:06:55.040
et cetera. And let's sink down to the bottom, the more communication and narrative aspects.

00:06:55.040 --> 00:07:01.679
This has many benefits. First of all, it allows us users to clearly see the main dependencies

00:07:01.679 --> 00:07:07.839
of our script at the top as we have things like external file references and package loads

00:07:07.839 --> 00:07:13.079
right where the user opens the document. Similarly, by grouping like pieces of code

00:07:13.079 --> 00:07:17.359
together, we can more easily start to see patterns throughout the code and get a sense

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:22.839
where we can later consolidate. And finally, often we'll be working on an analysis with

00:07:22.839 --> 00:07:27.799
colleagues that don't code and having all of the more narrative elements consolidated

00:07:27.799 --> 00:07:32.320
at the bottom may make it easier for them to find places where they can actually jump

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:37.720
in and edit the text parts in RMarkdown without being kind of intimidated by large blocks

00:07:37.720 --> 00:07:43.720
of code sprinkled throughout. Again, there's another great opportunity here to leverage

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:50.760
the RStudio IDE for even more synergy and take advantage of some tips like naming your

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:57.399
chunks and commenting your code with the quadruple dash, as you see in this example. The combination

00:07:57.399 --> 00:08:02.279
of these two features allows you to create a really friendly, nice table of contents

00:08:02.279 --> 00:08:08.239
that you can pop out to help a user navigate your script better and jump to the exact component

00:08:08.239 --> 00:08:14.959
that they want to work on. So after we've done all of this rearranging, one of the main

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:20.720
benefits of that is it can more easily help you understand related parts of your script

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:26.239
and find places where we can cut out duplicate code and replace these with functions for

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:32.599
an even more streamlined approach. As a somewhat trivial example of this, in an exploratory

00:08:32.599 --> 00:08:37.679
data analysis part of your workflow, you probably end up visualizing the relationship between

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:43.299
multiple variables and a lot of related plots. Doing this without functions leads to a lot

00:08:43.299 --> 00:08:48.559
of code that's both repeated and efficiently, but also makes it harder to tell exactly what

00:08:48.559 --> 00:08:53.520
piece of those lines is changing. All I'm actually changing there is the variable being

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:58.840
plotted on the y-axis, but it kind of takes some staring at it to tell. Instead, breaking

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:03.359
these apart into separate chunks to define my function and then to use my function gives

00:09:03.359 --> 00:09:08.840
me numerous benefits. First, if I want to change something about those plots, like theme,

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:15.159
I can easily just change that code in one place instead of multiple places. And secondly,

00:09:15.159 --> 00:09:20.359
from a more literate programming perspective, it's much easier in the view on the right

00:09:20.359 --> 00:09:27.359
to see what stayed the same versus what's changed between iterations. This is also a

00:09:27.359 --> 00:09:33.880
good time to start thinking about adding in R Oxygen 2 comments to your R Markdown. For

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:39.039
those that haven't ever built a package, R Oxygen 2 is the tool that you'll use to document

00:09:39.039 --> 00:09:44.239
functions and create the help pages that we've all likely seen at some point when we've pulled

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:49.640
out up R documentation. But even before you're building a package, you can easily in the

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:56.640
R Studio IDE add in this R Oxygen 2 skeleton and use that to document your function. This

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:01.320
is nice because it's a format that users are already used to seeing and gives them the

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:05.820
content they expect to know about a function. It can also help you think more critically

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:09.919
about the design of your functions because it forces you to almost make a contract with

00:10:09.919 --> 00:10:15.840
yourself about precisely what those inputs and those outputs ought to look like. So now

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:20.919
that we've cleaned up the actual content of our code a lot, one final step to consider

00:10:20.919 --> 00:10:25.960
at this point is also cleaning up the style. And we have many great R packages to help

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:32.760
out here, including the lintar, styler, and spelling packages. Lintars and stylers help

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:40.080
us adhere to a specific style guide for our script by either flagging for us to change

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:46.919
or by proactively themselves editing our script to make them adhere to certain rules

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:52.640
such as rules about spacing and indentation. And spelling similarly can help us catch typos

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:59.559
in our code for the cleanest possible view of our report. So going through all these

00:10:59.559 --> 00:11:05.840
steps, we've now really done a lot of work to move our R Markdown to something that's

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:10.239
pretty sustainable, pretty readable, pretty navigable. And in some cases, this in and

00:11:10.239 --> 00:11:15.719
of itself may be a really good stopping point. In resource-constrained environments, if you

00:11:15.719 --> 00:11:20.000
don't have a good way to share files with a colleague, a single file can be very easy

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:25.440
to send. If you don't have access to a good version control system, it can be very easy

00:11:25.440 --> 00:11:30.039
to just take a diff between versions. So there are some benefits to leaving things in a single

00:11:30.039 --> 00:11:35.239
file. Finally, you can also quickly refresh your code by just running one single file

00:11:35.239 --> 00:11:41.599
in isolation. However, these still can be sometimes lengthy, monolithic, and sort of

00:11:41.599 --> 00:11:47.559
intimidating to new users. And you may actually be forcing R Markdown to do a lot more computation

00:11:47.559 --> 00:11:53.159
than necessary any time you want to know. So if these sound like problems to you, we

00:11:53.159 --> 00:12:00.520
may want to consider moving from a file to an R project. An R project looks something

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:06.280
like this. And at a high level, our goal is to take a lot of the assets we have in

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:12.359
our single file R Markdown document and break them apart and modularize them into many different

00:12:12.359 --> 00:12:18.359
folders with semantic meaning. This can be very helpful if you or your organization uses

00:12:18.359 --> 00:12:22.719
a very standardized file structure across projects, because everyone will know where

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:27.799
to find specific data assets within a project. For example, one structure I like is shown

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:32.559
here on the screen, where I would save my actual R Markdown report and the output of

00:12:32.559 --> 00:12:38.760
that in my analysis folder. I put a lot of those functions that I defined and other little

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:44.320
bits of R code, such as those that read and process data, in a variety of R scripts in

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:52.080
my SRC folder. And I can save both my raw data as well as data artifacts that I create

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:56.840
throughout the process in different data folders. And finally, it's a good place to have

00:12:56.840 --> 00:13:03.080
catch-all files for different types of documentation or external pieces of context. This

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:07.679
allows me to create a much leaner R Markdown, where I just read in the minimal amount of

00:13:07.679 --> 00:13:13.760
resources from these files that I actually need. To take two more specific examples of

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:19.239
what this looks like, instead of defining both a function and calling that function in the

00:13:19.239 --> 00:13:25.960
same R Markdown, I can break that up and define my R function in a modularized script that

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:32.440
could be easily stolen and repurposed in another analysis. And I could simply load that in

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:39.359
by executing that code remotely with the source function in my R Markdown.

00:13:39.359 --> 00:13:44.520
Another big kind of step change benefit by going through this process is in your actual

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:49.679
data processing. Instead of doing all of your data processing within your R Markdown, I

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:55.119
tend to think about doing it in three different steps. First, I use some R scripts to access

00:13:55.159 --> 00:14:00.719
my data from my database or my API or wherever that data is coming from, and save that raw

00:14:00.719 --> 00:14:06.280
data in a read-only data file. Then, through, again, a variety of R scripts that might help

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:12.239
me with a lot of my data cleaning and wrangling and model fitting, I can create a lot of smaller

00:14:12.239 --> 00:14:18.039
data artifacts and have only those be what I read into my R Markdown. This means that

00:14:18.039 --> 00:14:23.080
I can run my R Markdown much faster without having to, like, repeat many long, lengthy

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.400
simulations or model builds or whatever it is you may be doing if I just want to make

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:33.919
some small change. And it also removes upstream dependencies on external systems, like APIs

00:14:33.919 --> 00:14:39.080
or databases, to be live and be working. If you just want to do something really small,

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:44.479
like change it, fix the typo in your R Markdown, you don't want to not be able to do that just

00:14:44.479 --> 00:14:48.799
because for some reason your database wasn't running.

00:14:48.799 --> 00:14:53.440
And one final note on projects. There exists a lot of great packages out there to help

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:59.200
you set up these projects, and some of them also have different opinionated file structures,

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:03.719
a little different maybe than the exact one I showed here, but very similar in spirit.

00:15:03.719 --> 00:15:08.200
So I definitely encourage you to check out use this project template and starters to

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:13.359
find the one that works best for you. And also making a project is a great time to think

00:15:13.359 --> 00:15:18.880
more about managing your package dependencies that are going into that project. And next

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:25.320
step after my talk is a talk on RM, so you'll get to learn a lot more about that shortly.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:31.119
So again, stepping back a minute to take a view of where we are, we now have a pretty

00:15:31.119 --> 00:15:38.440
well refactored analytical project as opposed to a file. And some benefits of this are that

00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:43.200
we can easily, like, we've really broken apart all sorts of pieces that might be independently

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:49.239
useful and put them in a place where they're very easily found and accessed to be repurposed.

00:15:49.239 --> 00:15:53.119
But at the same time, because we're in sort of project mode, we've really preserved a

00:15:53.119 --> 00:15:59.200
lot of the context specific to our individual analysis while doing this. So for people that

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:04.559
are more interested in building off of our analysis or taking the actual, like, learnings

00:16:04.559 --> 00:16:08.479
from what we were trying, the question we were trying to answer, it's still very easy

00:16:08.479 --> 00:16:15.440
to do that. However, for that very reason, projects can still cause some confusion because

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:20.119
they kind of blur the line sometimes between what's a tool versus what's part of a higher

00:16:20.119 --> 00:16:26.159
level process that solves a class of problems versus your individual problem. If you want

00:16:26.159 --> 00:16:31.520
to focus mostly on solving that broad class of problems, that's when we can move to a

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:37.719
full-blown R package. To me, one magical thing about R packages

00:16:37.719 --> 00:16:43.719
that I didn't realize when I first started using R was they're really as simple as saving

00:16:43.719 --> 00:16:48.880
a lot of R code in the right places. And there's pretty clear one-to-one mapping between the

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:53.979
kind of structure you might use for a project that I've talked about previously to the kind

00:16:53.979 --> 00:16:59.200
of structure you'd use for an R package. All of the functions that we just broke up into

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:04.839
separate R scripts translate easily, go right into a single R folder.

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:09.800
The actual R Markdown that we've been working with this whole time can actually serve numerous

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:15.400
purposes. It can either go in your package as an R Markdown template, so users of your

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:20.719
package immediately have some code they can use to start playing with and experimenting

00:17:20.719 --> 00:17:26.719
with and a working R Markdown example of how to use what you've built. And they can also

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:32.239
be repurposed as vignettes and long-form documentation to really teach people more

00:17:32.239 --> 00:17:35.719
deeply about how to think about the problem that they're working on.

00:17:35.719 --> 00:17:40.640
Similarly, all of the data artifacts we created, if we're careful to anonymize them and take

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:45.920
out anything that we shouldn't be sharing with the public, can be very useful as examples

00:17:45.920 --> 00:17:50.680
in your data package. By shipping example data in the data folder, this gives us a great

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:56.280
way to build more vignettes, to conduct unit testing, and to give examples in your R Oxygen

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:02.040
documentation. Really, the only two things we're missing at this stage are a man folder

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:08.079
where the documentation manual lives and the test folder for unit tests.

00:18:08.079 --> 00:18:13.319
And at this point, I doubt it should surprise anyone here that there are more great R packages

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:19.400
to help us go this last mile. First of all, once again, the use this package is phenomenal

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:24.319
for helping us set up the package infrastructure we need and making sure we do, in fact, save

00:18:24.319 --> 00:18:28.959
all those individual package assets in the right places with the right file structures

00:18:28.959 --> 00:18:33.359
and configuration files to make everything flow through seamlessly.

00:18:33.359 --> 00:18:40.520
Dev tools can automatically generate our R documentation from the R Oxygen comments that

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:45.880
we have already wrote many steps back in this process. And TestFat provides a really friendly

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:52.239
interface for doing unit testing, which, quite honestly, objectively, if we want to trust

00:18:52.239 --> 00:18:57.199
the outcome of any analysis, we probably even could have thought about doing many steps

00:18:57.199 --> 00:19:03.239
earlier in this process. And beyond all of those absolute requirements,

00:19:03.239 --> 00:19:08.719
R even goes above and beyond what we need. And there also exists Packagedown, which can

00:19:08.719 --> 00:19:14.520
similarly reuse all of those great assets you made throughout your project and throughout

00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:20.680
the R Markdown-driven development process and create a very user-friendly, attractive,

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:27.239
polished website to help people learn about and use your analytical tool.

00:19:27.239 --> 00:19:32.500
So now we've created kind of the spectrum of possible outputs and possible analytical

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:38.420
outcomes of our R Markdown-driven development process. I think all of us are probably very

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:43.079
well aware what incremental benefits the package provides. It's, of course, one of the most

00:19:43.079 --> 00:19:49.479
formal distribution mechanisms, especially if you have access to a CRAN or a CRAN-like

00:19:49.479 --> 00:19:57.680
repository to share your work. And it also adds benefits because it provides a very formal

00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:01.880
and familiar way for people to learn about and engage with your tool. Pretty much any

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:07.359
R user is used to working with an R package. That said, kind of the tradeoff again that

00:20:07.359 --> 00:20:14.319
exists here is that at this point, we've abstracted very far away from our initial problem. And

00:20:14.319 --> 00:20:20.239
if simply recreating your work is, you think, going to be the primary goal of future users,

00:20:20.239 --> 00:20:28.040
then maybe we've gone a bit too far. So in summary, no matter which path you choose,

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:33.119
your original R Markdown analysis can be a great starting point for a very wide variety

00:20:33.119 --> 00:20:38.800
of data products. And by leveraging all the work you did in conducting your initial analysis,

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:42.800
you're much closer than you may realize to building a very sustainable and empathetic

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:48.199
data tool. Thank you all very much for coming in your time today. If you're interested in

00:20:48.199 --> 00:20:56.280
learning more, I have a blog post on this topic that you can find at tiny.cc slash rmddd.

00:20:56.280 --> 00:21:08.479
And if there's time remaining, I'm happy to take any questions.

00:21:08.479 --> 00:21:11.920
Thank you, Emily. That was excellent. We have time for just a couple questions, maybe just

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:16.520
one. The most popular is, how does this workflow change if the end result is an automated scheduled

00:21:16.520 --> 00:21:21.359
job? I think that probably can vary in a couple

00:21:21.359 --> 00:21:27.000
of ways depending on how complicated the job is. I know I've been reading about and learning

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:32.599
about RStudio Connect some recently, and I think that actually has a lot of good options

00:21:32.599 --> 00:21:37.959
for automation based purely out of that original R Markdown. So I think that could be another

00:21:37.959 --> 00:21:43.079
good use case where the one-file R Markdown approach, even if it is handling kind of the

00:21:43.079 --> 00:21:51.040
full ETL process, is actually a good solution because it can still, some of the rerunning

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:55.800
problems aren't really a problem because rerunning your work is actually what you're trying to

00:21:55.800 --> 00:22:01.719
accomplish. But for some more complicated batch processes, even if you're automating

00:22:01.719 --> 00:22:06.560
them, you'd still probably want to go all the way and build the package and then go

00:22:06.560 --> 00:22:12.400
back and use the tools you've created to build the job if you want to have more robust

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:16.880
and well-tested and well-documented components to that batch job.

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:17.359
Thank you again.

